<subSubSection pageId="29" pageNumber="30" type="nomenclature">
<paragraph blockId="29.[151,739,151,211]" box="[151,603,151,178]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">
<heading bold="true" box="[151,603,151,178]" fontSize="11" level="1" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" reason="1">
<taxonomicName authority="Atallah, 1967" authorityName="Atallah" authorityYear="1967" box="[151,603,151,178]" class="Mammalia" family="Muridae" genus="Acomys" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" phylum="Chordata" rank="subSpecies" species="russatus" subSpecies="lewisi">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,603,151,178]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,430,151,177]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Acomys russatus lewisi</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation box="[436,603,152,178]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" refId="ref31502" refString="Atallah, S. I. &amp; Harrison, D. L. (1967) New records of rodents, bats and insectivores from the Arabian Peninsula. Journal of Zoology, London, 153 (3), 311 - 319. https: // doi. org / 10.1111 / j. 1469 - 7998.1967. tb 04065. x" type="journal article">Atallah, 1967</bibRefCitation>
</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="29.[151,739,151,211]" box="[151,739,186,211]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,343,186,211]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Common name:</emphasis>
Melanistic or Lewis’ spiny mouse.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="29" pageNumber="30" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="29.[151,1436,258,931]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,266,258,283]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Diagnosis</emphasis>
: This is a melanistic form of 
<taxonomicName box="[593,738,259,283]" class="Mammalia" family="Muridae" genus="Acomys" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" phylum="Chordata" rank="subSpecies" subSpecies="russtaus">
<emphasis box="[593,738,259,283]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">A. r. russtaus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, similar in size and form, but covered with black spines on the back and dark gray fur on the ventral side (
<figureCitation box="[632,746,294,319]" captionStart="FIGURE 30" captionStartId="29.[151,250,1718,1740]" captionTargetBox="[264,1323,983,1696]" captionTargetId="figure@29.[264,1323,983,1696]" captionTargetPageId="29" captionText="FIGURE 30.Lewis spiny mouse, Acomys russatuslewisi, from Azraq." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1202837/files/figure.png" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Figure 30</figureCitation>
). Skul morphology is shown in 
<figureCitation box="[1102,1213,294,319]" captionStart="FIGURE 31" captionStartId="30.[151,250,2007,2029]" captionTargetBox="[281,1306,183,1997]" captionTargetId="figure@30.[281,1306,183,1997]" captionTargetPageId="30" captionText="FIGURE 31. A. Dorsal,B. Ventral, and C. Lateral views of the skull for Acomys russatus lewisi." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1202839/files/figure.png" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Figure 31</figureCitation>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="29.[151,1436,258,931]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,314,330,355]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Localities</emphasis>
: 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[329,530,330,355]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Previous records</emphasis>
. Azraq (
<bibRefCitation box="[628,799,330,355]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" refId="ref31502" refString="Atallah, S. I. &amp; Harrison, D. L. (1967) New records of rodents, bats and insectivores from the Arabian Peninsula. Journal of Zoology, London, 153 (3), 311 - 319. https: // doi. org / 10.1111 / j. 1469 - 7998.1967. tb 04065. x" type="journal article">Atallah, 1967a</bibRefCitation>
); Wādī Rajil near Jāwá (Searight, 1987); Buqay’awiyah, Wādī Salma (
<bibRefCitation box="[303,600,366,391]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" refId="ref30180" refString="Abu Baker, M. &amp; Amr, Z. (2003 a) A morphometric and taxonomic revision of the genus Gerbillus in Jordan with notes on its current distribution. Zoologische Abhandlungen (Dresden), 53, 177 - 204." type="journal article">Abu Baker &amp; Amr, 2003a</bibRefCitation>
). 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[619,768,366,391]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">New records</emphasis>
. Ernbeh, Marab Omish (
<figureCitation box="[1046,1160,366,391]" captionStart="FIGURE 32" captionStartId="31.[151,250,1397,1419]" captionTargetBox="[275,1307,202,1342]" captionTargetId="figure@31.[264,1323,167,1375]" captionTargetPageId="31" captionText="FIGURE 32. Distribution of Lewis’s spiny mouse, Acomys russatus lewisi." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1202841/files/figure.png" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Figure 32</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="29" pageNumber="30" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="29.[151,1436,258,931]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,291,402,427]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Habitat</emphasis>
: This subspecies is confined to the black lava desert of eastern 
<collectingCountry box="[1004,1082,402,427]" name="Jordan" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Jordan</collectingCountry>
. It occupies rocky areas around Azraq and extends throughout the black lava desert into 
<collectingCountry box="[783,842,438,463]" name="Syria" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Syria</collectingCountry>
and northern 
<collectingCountry box="[999,1149,438,463]" name="Saudi Arabia" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Saudi Arabia</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="29" pageNumber="30" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="29.[151,1436,258,931]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,298,474,499]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Biology:</emphasis>
Individuals of this species were successfully kept in captivity; they were fed sunflower seeds and supplied with water. The activity peak in the laboratory was seen in the early morning hours of the day. The ability of interbreeding between the two forms of this species (
<taxonomicName authorityName="russatus (Wagner" authorityYear="1840" box="[780,927,547,571]" class="Mammalia" family="Muridae" genus="Acomys" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" phylum="Chordata" rank="subSpecies" species="russatus" subSpecies="russatus">
<emphasis box="[780,927,547,571]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">A. r. russatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Atallah" authorityYear="1967" box="[983,1102,546,571]" class="Mammalia" family="Muridae" genus="Acomys" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" phylum="Chordata" rank="subSpecies" species="russatus" subSpecies="lewisi">
<emphasis box="[983,1102,546,571]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">A. r. lewisi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), was tested in the laboratory with an adult 
<taxonomicName authorityName="russatus (Wagner" authorityYear="1840" box="[304,450,583,606]" class="Mammalia" family="Muridae" genus="Acomys" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" phylum="Chordata" rank="subSpecies" species="russatus" subSpecies="russatus">
<emphasis box="[304,450,583,606]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">A. r. russatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
male from Wādī Ramm and an adult 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Atallah" authorityYear="1967" box="[874,992,582,607]" class="Mammalia" family="Muridae" genus="Acomys" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" phylum="Chordata" rank="subSpecies" species="russatus" subSpecies="lewisi">
<emphasis box="[874,992,582,607]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">A. r. lewisi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
female from Azraq ed Duruz. No signs of any aggressive behavior were seen during the time of the experiment. The animals were kept together for several months, however, they failed to reproduce, while controlled groups of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Atallah" authorityYear="1967" box="[962,1084,654,679]" class="Mammalia" family="Muridae" genus="Acomys" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" phylum="Chordata" rank="subSpecies" species="russatus" subSpecies="lewisi">
<emphasis box="[962,1084,654,679]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">A. r. lewisi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
gave birth to 3–5 young (
<bibRefCitation pageId="29" pageNumber="30" refId="ref30224" refString="Abu Baker, M. &amp; Amr, Z. (2003 b) Rodent diversity in the Northeastern Desert of Jordan, with special reference on the ecology of Gerbillus cheesmani. (Mammalia: Rodentia). Casopis Narodniho Muzea, Rada prirodovedna, 172 (1 - 4), 141 - 152." type="journal article">Abu Baker &amp; Amr, 2003b</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="29" pageNumber="30" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="29.[151,1436,258,931]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,308,726,751]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Remarks</emphasis>
: Bates (1994) considered the species 
<taxonomicName box="[742,840,726,751]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Amaranthaceae" genus="Atriplex" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="lewisi">
<emphasis box="[742,840,726,751]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">A. lewisi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as a synonym for 
<emphasis box="[1056,1297,726,751]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Wilson &amp; Reeder" baseAuthorityYear="2005" box="[1056,1186,727,750]" class="Mammalia" family="Muridae" genus="Acomys" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="russatus">A. russatus</taxonomicName>
. 
<taxonomicName box="[1199,1297,726,751]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Amaranthaceae" genus="Atriplex" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="lewisi">A. lewisi</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
is darker in color and apparently is confined to the black lava deserts of Azraq and Jāwá (
<bibRefCitation box="[1029,1200,762,787]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" refId="ref31502" refString="Atallah, S. I. &amp; Harrison, D. L. (1967) New records of rodents, bats and insectivores from the Arabian Peninsula. Journal of Zoology, London, 153 (3), 311 - 319. https: // doi. org / 10.1111 / j. 1469 - 7998.1967. tb 04065. x" type="journal article">Atallah, 1967a</bibRefCitation>
; Searight, 1987).The karyotype for specimens collected from 
<collectingCountry box="[616,691,798,823]" name="Jordan" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Jordan</collectingCountry>
yielded a diploid chromosome number of 66 and a fundamental number was 76–92. The autosomal set consists of 12 biarmed pairs (subtelocentric) and 20 pairs of acrocentric chromosomes. The X chromosome is subtelocentric, and the Y chromosome is acrocentric (Qumsiyeh 
<emphasis box="[1302,1351,870,895]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">et al</emphasis>
., 1986; Sözen 
<emphasis box="[219,268,906,931]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">et al</emphasis>
., 2008).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
